06265nam a22008415i 9781442679382DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182003onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426793827 a10.3138/97814426793822doi  a(DE-B1597)497184  a(OCoLC)1078915616  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a303.37200aRisk and Morality /ced. by Aaron Doyle, Diana Ericson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (464 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGreen College Thematic Lecture Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Risk and Morality -- tPART ONE. Theories of Risk and Morality -- tIntroduction -- t2. Risk and Dirt -- t3. The Rise of Risk -- t4. Risk and Morality: Three Framing Devices -- tPART TWO. New Moralities of Risk and Responsibility -- tIntroduction -- t5. New Moralities of Risk and Political Responsibility -- t6. Risk Management and the Responsible Organization -- t7. Risk and Moralization in Everyday Life -- t8. From Risk to Precaution: The Rationalities of Personal Crime Prevention -- tPART THREE. The Moral Risks of Insurance -- tIntroduction -- t9. Moral Uncertainties: Contract Law and Distinctions between Speculation, Gambling, and Insurance -- t10. Containing the Promise of Insurance: Adverse Selection and Risk Classification -- t11. Insurers as Moral Actors -- t12. The Moral Risks of Private Justice: The Case of Insurance Fraud -- tPART FOUR. Governing Risky Desires -- tIntroduction -- t13. Risking Rescue: High Altitude Rescue as Moral Risk and Moral Opportunity -- t14. The Neurochemical Self and Its Anomalies -- t15. Targeted Governance and the Problem of Desire -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRisk and Morality examines how decisions about risk and uncertainty relate to moral principles and ethical conduct. Editors Richard Ericson and Aaron Doyle have brought together in this volume a selection of original essays on the topic by renowned scholars in the disciplines of philosophy, sociology, law, political science, geography, criminology, and accounting from Canada, the United States, England, France, and Australia. Presenting cutting-edge theory and research, the essays analyse the broader social, political, economic and cultural dimensions of risk and morality.The concept of risk has become pervasive in recent years in political discourse, popular culture, organizational communications, and everyday life. The contributors' respective research projects on risk and morality in politics, business, legal regulation, crime prevention, insurance, extreme sports, and biotechnology provide original empirical evidence to substantiate their theories and address the ideological and policy relevance of their work. Collectively, the contributors explain why risk is such a key aspect of Western culture, and demonstrate that new regimes for risk management are transforming social integration, value-based reasoning and morality. Further, they illustrate that these new regimes do not necessarily foster more responsible conduct or greater accountability in institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aA. Heimer, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD. Haggerty, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Aaron, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov